# [Access files in /var/mobile/Containers/Data/Application without jailbreaking iPhone](/questions/38064042/access-files-in-var-mobile-containers-data-application-without-jailbreaking-iph)
   [Ask Question](/questions/ask)      Asked 9 years, 3 months ago   Modified [7 years ago](?lastactivity)   Viewed 1.1m times    Part of [Mobile Development](/collectives/mobile-dev) Collective               52               A program logs some message in directory /var/mobile/Containers/Data/Application on iPhone. Is there any way I can get access to this directory without jailbreaking iPhone? If no, is there any directory on iPhone that I can log into and read my logs without jailbreaking?
      

- [ios](/questions/tagged/ios)

- [iphone](/questions/tagged/iphone)

          [Share](/q/38064042)   [Improve this question](/posts/38064042/edit)    Follow            asked Jun 27, 2016 at 22:14       [ZigZagZebra](/users/4592639/zigzagzebra)  1,45933 gold badges1717 silver badges2727 bronze badges            [Add a comment](#)             
##  1 Answer  
      Sorted by:       Highest score (default)   Trending (recent votes count more)   Date modified (newest first)   Date created (oldest first)                  184                      If this is your app, if you connect the device to your computer, you can use the "Devices" option on Xcode's "Window" menu and then download the app's data container to your computer. Just select your app from the list of installed apps, and click on the "gear" icon and choose "Download Container". 
 
 Once you've downloaded it, right click on the file in the Finder and choose "Show Package Contents".
         [Share](/a/38064225)   [Improve this answer](/posts/38064225/edit)    Follow            [edited Jun 27, 2016 at 22:36](/posts/38064225/revisions)               answered Jun 27, 2016 at 22:31       [Rob](/users/1271826/rob)  441k7474 gold badges848848 silver badges1.1k1.1k bronze badges             Sign up to request clarification or add additional context in comments.

Is there any way that I can get older logs?   0  Reply        [Rob](/users/1271826/rob) [Over a year ago](#comment63568567_38064225)    AFAIK, that container contains everything on the device. Maybe app was reinstalled at some point. Or maybe the logs were purged at some point due to storage constraints. But I'm pretty sure this container contains everything that is available.   1  Reply        [ZigZagZebra](/users/4592639/zigzagzebra) [Over a year ago](#comment63568705_38064225)    Oh, yeah.
